# 1d: partitioning 

# Get the size of each partition
def displaypartitions(df):
    num = df.rdd.getNumPartitions()
    print("Partitions:", num)
    df.withColumn("partitionId", F.spark_partition_id())\
        .groupBy("partitionId")\
        .count()\
        .orderBy(F.asc("count"))\
        .show(num)
    
displaypartitions(crimes_df)

  • ID, integer -> string (ID should not be changed and strings are an immutable data type)

  • updated on, string -> datetype (should be in date format)
  • IUCR, string -> integer (the values in this column are integers)

# find day of the week and month with highest and least crime counts on average 


# make column for day of the week
crimes_df = crimes_df.withColumn("Day", F.date_format("Date", "EEE"))


# group by the Day of the week, count total number of rows (to get total number of crimes) for each day of the week
# and count how many unique instances for each day of the week there were in the entire df 
# get average using total crime count and unique occurrences 
day_res = crimes_df.groupBy("Day").agg(F.count("*").alias("count"), F.countDistinct("Date").alias("occurrences"))
day_res = day_res.withColumn("Average", F.col("count") / F.col("occurrences"))
day_res.select("Day", "Average").orderBy(col("Average").desc()).show()

# need to make a column for years in order to get the unique month counts for calculating averages
crimes_df = crimes_df.withColumn("Year", F.year("Date")) 

# same logic as before, group by month and count how many crimes occured each month 
month_res = crimes_df.groupBy("Month").agg(F.count("*").alias("count"))

# find distinct months across years (can't use same method as Days because those can come from dates easily)
month_counts = crimes_df.select("Month", "Year").distinct().groupBy("Month")
month_counts = month_counts.agg(F.countDistinct("Year").alias("occurrences"))

# merge into one df to make calculating average easier 
month_res = month_res.join(month_counts, on="Month", how="left")

# calculate average
month_res = month_res.withColumn("Average", F.col("count") / F.col("occurrences"))

# Step 6: Display the result
month_res.select("Month", "Average").orderBy(col("Average").desc()).show()

# build a correlation matrix
numeric_columns = [col for col, dtype in new_df.dtypes if dtype in ('int', 'double')]
vec_assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=numeric_columns, outputCol="features")
df_with_features = vec_assembler.transform(new_df.dropna(subset=numeric_columns))

# Step 3: Calculate the correlation matrix
matrix = Correlation.corr(df_with_features, "features").head()[0]

# Step 4: Convert the correlation matrix to a Pandas DataFrame for easier viewing
corr_matrix = matrix.toArray()
corr_df = pd.DataFrame(corr_matrix, columns=numeric_columns, index=numeric_columns)
